theorem closure_diff_frontier_eq_interior {X : Type*} [TopologicalSpace X] (A : Set X) :
    closure A \ frontier A = interior A := by
  -- We prove the two inclusions separately and then use extensionality.
  ext x
  constructor
  · -- `x ∈ closure A \ frontier A → x ∈ interior A`
    intro hx
    have hx_cl : x ∈ closure A := hx.1
    have hx_not_front : x ∉ frontier A := hx.2
    -- If `x` were not in `interior A`, it would be in the frontier,
    -- contradicting `hx_not_front`.
    by_cases hx_int : x ∈ interior A
    · exact hx_int
    ·
      -- Show that `x ∈ frontier A`, contradicting `hx_not_front`.
      have hx_front : x ∈ frontier A := by
        -- `frontier A = closure A \ interior A`
        have h_eq := frontier_eq_closure_diff_interior (X := X) (A := A)
        have : x ∈ closure A \ interior A := And.intro hx_cl hx_int
        simpa [h_eq] using this
      exact (hx_not_front hx_front).elim
  · -- `x ∈ interior A → x ∈ closure A \ frontier A`
    intro hx_int
    -- Membership in `closure A`
    have hx_cl : x ∈ closure A := subset_closure (interior_subset hx_int)
    -- `x` is not in the frontier because it lies in the interior.
    have hx_not_front : x ∉ frontier A := by
      intro hx_front
      have h_subset :=
        frontier_subset_compl_interior (X := X) (A := A) hx_front
      exact h_subset hx_int
    exact And.intro hx_cl hx_not_front

theorem frontier_frontier_subset_closed {X : Type*} [TopologicalSpace X] {A : Set X}
    (hA : IsClosed A) :
    frontier (frontier (A : Set X)) ⊆ A := by
  intro x hx
  -- Step 1: `frontier A ⊆ A` because `A` is closed.
  have h_sub : frontier A ⊆ A :=
    frontier_subset_of_closed (A := A) hA
  -- Step 2: Taking closures preserves inclusions, and `closure A = A`.
  have h_closure : closure (frontier A) ⊆ A := by
    have h := closure_mono h_sub
    simpa [hA.closure_eq] using h
  -- Step 3: `x` lies in `closure (frontier A)` by definition of the frontier,
  -- hence in `A` by `h_closure`.
  exact h_closure hx.1
